    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i get the twin thing but it still feels kinda weird. like, why does the second particle 'know' what the first one did instantly? even einstein called it 'spooky action at a distance' right? can u explain why it's considered so spooky or weird compared to normal stuff?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"spooky action at a distance\" moniker was indeed coined by Einstein, and it's a fitting description. The reason entanglement seems so weird is that it defies our classical intuition about space and time. In classical physics, information can only travel at a finite speed, so if you measure the state of one particle, the other particle would have to wait for that information to propagate to it, which would take some time.\n\nBut with entanglement, it's as if the information is transmitted instantaneously, regardless of the distance between the particles. This is because, at the quantum level, particles can exist in a superposition of states, meaning they can be in multiple states simultaneously. When you measure the state of one particle, you're essentially collapsing the superposition, which instantly affects the other entangled particle, regardless of the distance between them.\n\nThink of it like a game of \" telephone\" where the information is transmitted through a network of particles, but instead of a physical wire, it's transmitted through the quantum vacuum. The particles act as a kind of \"quantum messenger\" that allows the information to be transmitted instantaneously, which is what Einstein found so unsettling.\n\nIt's worth noting that entanglement is",
